Hardly had Napoleon’s translator spoken when the Cossack, seized by a sort of amazement, offered not a word more and rode on with his eyes constantly fixed on this conqueror, whose name had penetrated as far as him, across the steppes of the East. All his loquacity had suddenly stopped, to give place to a feeling of na&#239;ve and silent admiration. Napoleon, after rewarding him, set him free, like a bird that one sends back to the fields where it was born.


